16:26.200 --> 16:29.640
I don't see anything particularly
amusing about this, Mrs Leighton.

16:29.640 --> 16:31.400
I'm sorry, really, I'm sorry.

16:31.400 --> 16:35.400
Now, we all know where our best
source of protein comes from,

16:35.400 --> 16:36.440
do we not?

16:36.440 --> 16:37.680
Of course we do.

16:37.680 --> 16:39.560
Yes, meet Sammy.

16:39.560 --> 16:43.560
(LAUGHS)

16:46.960 --> 16:48.560
Ehrlich, please, stop it.

16:48.560 --> 16:49.720
Oh, I can't stop.

16:49.720 --> 16:51.800
Happy fingers.

16:51.800 --> 16:53.400
This from a man who, this morning,

16:53.400 --> 16:55.520
was moaning that he hadn't
slept in two days.

16:55.520 --> 16:56.560
What's more important

16:56.560 --> 16:58.520
is I haven't slept
with  anyone in two months.

16:58.520 --> 17:00.480
Come on, last Thursday with Emma.

17:00.480 --> 17:03.320
No, no, bunk beds in on-call
do not count.

17:03.320 --> 17:05.880
I still don't understand
why you're so happy.

17:05.880 --> 17:07.000
Because, my friend,

17:07.000 --> 17:09.400
in roughly 20 minutes I'm going
to be cruising into port,

17:09.400 --> 17:11.480
ready to drop anchor.

17:11.480 --> 17:13.960
Now I know how Columbus
felt finding a New World.

17:13.960 --> 17:14.520
You've got a date.

17:14.520 --> 17:18.200
You've got a date.

17:18.200 --> 17:20.920
(CHOKES) With who?

17:20.920 --> 17:22.720
Well, specifics aren't
really important

17:22.720 --> 17:25.640
but I can tell you she is a junior.

17:25.640 --> 17:28.160
You're going out with
a candy striper?

17:28.160 --> 17:30.640
Erlich, have you ever had
a conversation with one of them?

17:30.640 --> 17:33.680
Some of them can barely read!

17:33.680 --> 17:37.680
How can you say that?

17:38.880 --> 17:40.800
Eve's a real slugger.

17:40.800 --> 17:42.200
I was worried, there, for a while

17:42.200 --> 17:44.080
but you should have seen
her this morning.

17:44.080 --> 17:46.400
She snapped out of her
post-op depression

17:46.400 --> 17:48.240
and is raring to get
out of this place.

17:48.240 --> 17:49.360
Can you blame her?

17:49.360 --> 17:50.400
No, I can't!

17:50.400 --> 17:52.120
You know what she
got me to agree to?

17:52.120 --> 17:55.600
Evidently the kids at her school
are confused about the transplant.

17:55.600 --> 17:59.600
I promised to go down there this
week and explain it to them.

17:59.960 --> 18:02.360
The Selman foundation
renewed our grant

18:02.360 --> 18:04.840
only because of the success
of your work.

18:04.840 --> 18:06.280
Well, it's about time.

18:06.280 --> 18:08.960
You mean they've been sleeping
together for over a year?!

18:08.960 --> 18:11.000
Well, you know, evidently,

18:11.000 --> 18:12.760
they knew each other even
before he moved to town.

18:12.760 --> 18:13.800
they knew each other even
before he moved to town.

18:13.800 --> 18:14.880
Who's that?

18:14.880 --> 18:16.240
&lt; Joan Halloran and Bobby Caldwell.

18:16.240 --> 18:18.080
&lt; Joan Halloran and Bobby Caldwell.

18:18.080 --> 18:21.480
Luther Hawkins told me,
also about the accident.

18:21.480 --> 18:22.960
What accident?

18:22.960 --> 18:25.760
Bobby Caldwell was in Halloran's
apartment when he got mugged.

18:25.760 --> 18:27.600
Wait a minute here, wait a minute.

18:27.600 --> 18:30.280
Now, let me get this straight,
Caldwell and Halloran

18:30.280 --> 18:33.320
have been playing, "I've got
a secret," for the past year?!

18:33.320 --> 18:34.840
Hm-mm.

18:34.840 --> 18:36.560
Why am I always the last to know?

18:36.560 --> 18:40.560
Hm-mm-mm.

18:42.520 --> 18:46.520
'Mr Acorn, Mr John Acorn to fourth
floor nurses station.'

18:48.120 --> 18:49.880
Hi, Dad.

18:49.880 --> 18:51.240
Hi!

18:51.240 --> 18:53.120
What are you doing here?

18:53.120 --> 18:54.600
I've got something to tell you.

18:54.600 --> 18:58.440
I've made a decision,
I'm not going to Vassar.

18:58.440 --> 18:59.840
What?

18:59.840 --> 19:03.680
Dad, it's just too expensive,
it's too far away

19:03.680 --> 19:07.680
and, besides, anything I can learn
there I can study right here at BC.

19:08.400 --> 19:11.840
Does this have anything to do with
Mrs Catalano's leaving?

19:11.840 --> 19:14.160
Yeah, kind of.

19:14.160 --> 19:16.800
Lizzie, we'll find
another housekeeper.

19:16.800 --> 19:19.920
Dad, do you really think there are
that many housekeepers out there

19:19.920 --> 19:23.000
that are going to be willing
to take care of an autistic child?

19:23.000 --> 19:24.920
All we need is one.

19:24.920 --> 19:26.720
Don't worry, honey.

19:26.720 --> 19:29.000
I don't know,
it doesn't seem fair, Dad.

19:29.000 --> 19:31.080
I mean, you've spent your whole
life taking care of us

19:31.080 --> 19:34.200
and taking care of patients.

19:34.200 --> 19:38.200
You never seem to take any
time for yourself.

19:38.480 --> 19:40.920
I like my life just the way it is.

19:40.920 --> 19:44.920
I don't know, Dad, the older I get,

19:45.160 --> 19:47.480
I just think you should
date more often.

19:47.480 --> 19:51.160
I don't want you to grow
old all alone.

19:51.160 --> 19:53.080
Sweetheart, it's my choice.

19:53.080 --> 19:54.920
And, for now,
everything is just fine.

19:54.920 --> 19:56.720
Really?  Really.

19:56.720 --> 19:58.880
(OK.)

19:58.880 --> 20:01.520
Well, any time you want to bring
a lady home for the night

20:01.520 --> 20:03.960
it's OK by me.

20:03.960 --> 20:05.360
It is?

20:05.360 --> 20:06.400
Thank you.

20:06.400 --> 20:08.440
I got to get to play practice.

20:08.440 --> 20:09.600
All right, I'll see you at home.

20:09.600 --> 20:11.560
All right, I'll see you at home.

20:11.560 --> 20:12.880
Bye.

20:12.880 --> 20:13.920
Hey.

20:13.920 --> 20:16.040
Please, don't worry about it. &gt;

20:16.040 --> 20:17.880
Tommy and I will be just fine.

20:17.880 --> 20:19.680
OK. Bye.

20:19.680 --> 20:23.680
Bye-bye. &gt;

20:28.480 --> 20:32.360
I've, er, I've thought a lot about
you in the past couple of months.

20:32.360 --> 20:35.560
Yes, yes, that is so funny,
so have I.

20:35.560 --> 20:37.120
Ever since that night in the laundry

20:37.120 --> 20:39.840
I've felt there's something
very special between us.

20:39.840 --> 20:41.680
Well, I had a great time.

20:41.680 --> 20:42.720
Me too.

20:42.720 --> 20:45.560
Thanks.

20:45.560 --> 20:48.920
Whoa, whoa, Roberta, don't rush off!

20:48.920 --> 20:52.800
Don't you want to invite
me in for a cup of coffee?

20:52.800 --> 20:54.800
Oh, yes, oh, OK, come in.

20:54.800 --> 20:58.800
OK.

20:58.800 --> 21:01.960
Let me see now,
you take one lump, is that right?

21:01.960 --> 21:03.440
&lt; Yes, one lump.

21:03.440 --> 21:06.440
What a memory you've got, baby doll!
(CHUCKLES) Oh, you know what?

21:06.440 --> 21:07.480
Cancel, cancel!

21:07.480 --> 21:10.560
Change that to something,
kind of, carbonated, maybe.

21:10.560 --> 21:14.560
Oh, OK.

21:15.600 --> 21:17.000
Yahoo!

21:17.000 --> 21:18.920
Victor, what are you doing?

21:18.920 --> 21:22.160
Just getting comfortable. (CHUCKLES)

21:22.160 --> 21:25.280
Er...no.

21:25.280 --> 21:27.320
No, no, no, erm...

21:27.320 --> 21:29.120
What's the matter? Weak box spring?

21:29.120 --> 21:32.120
Ooh, yeah, kinky.

21:32.120 --> 21:33.360
Up!  What?

21:33.360 --> 21:36.080
You've got the wrong idea, Victor.

21:36.080 --> 21:37.840
No, I don't think I do, hun.

21:37.840 --> 21:40.360
Remember, I'm Dr Positive Influence,
OK?

21:40.360 --> 21:41.760
Even my pal Weiss said that...

21:41.760 --> 21:44.240
Your pal Weiss said that
I should be seeing men

21:44.240 --> 21:46.440
with a soft sexual persona -

21:46.440 --> 21:48.040
you immediately came to our minds.

21:48.040 --> 21:50.280
Let me tell you something
about Weiss for starters,

21:50.280 --> 21:52.000
the guy had a thing for his  mother.

21:52.000 --> 21:54.840
Well, Dr Weiss said that you would
try and impugn his credibility.

21:54.840 --> 21:57.640
What are you talking about?
This guy is a quack.

21:57.640 --> 22:00.840
Victor, I care about you.

22:00.840 --> 22:01.960
I care about you.

22:01.960 --> 22:05.320
And I really want
us to be friends but...

22:05.320 --> 22:08.920
Dr Weiss says that under
no circumstances...

22:08.920 --> 22:11.640
are you and I to have sex.

22:11.640 --> 22:13.760
(EXHALES)

22:13.760 --> 22:17.000
Under  no  circumstances?!

22:17.000 --> 22:21.000
(EXHALES) &gt;

22:25.040 --> 22:29.040
I think you should leave now.

22:29.440 --> 22:33.440
Oh, brother.

22:34.400 --> 22:38.400
It's because I'm wearing
a tie, isn't it?

22:39.240 --> 22:43.240
(EXHALES) I'm going to kill Weiss.

22:49.200 --> 22:50.240
&lt; (GASPING AND CHOKING)

22:50.240 --> 22:51.720
She's choking, she's a-aspirate.

22:51.720 --> 22:55.280
Give her suction,
we've got to clear her lungs.

22:55.280 --> 22:56.320
I'll get Craig, where is he?

22:56.320 --> 22:58.440
I'll get Craig, where is he?

22:58.440 --> 23:02.440
(COUGHS)

23:05.600 --> 23:09.600
There's a certain amount of bleeding
from the anterior suture line.

23:12.520 --> 23:13.920
BUZZER SOUNDS

23:13.920 --> 23:16.160
'Get that.'

23:16.160 --> 23:19.280
Dr Craig, we need you
in Eve Leighton's room.

23:19.280 --> 23:22.240
You'll have to wait, I'm at the most
crucial part of the bypass.

23:22.240 --> 23:24.200
Mrs Leighton may have aspirated.

23:24.200 --> 23:27.680
&lt; She vomited and is having
difficulty breathing.

23:27.680 --> 23:31.680
&lt; What you want to do?

23:32.000 --> 23:34.760
Check the board. Get me another
surgeon to take over here.

23:34.760 --> 23:38.760
Right away.

23:41.360 --> 23:43.000
How's the pulse?

23:43.000 --> 23:44.320
Still no response.

23:44.320 --> 23:48.320
Another amp of bicarb.

23:50.960 --> 23:53.040
&lt; 300 milligrams.

23:53.040 --> 23:56.040
Come on, Eve.

23:56.040 --> 23:57.880
BUZZER SOUNDS

23:57.880 --> 24:01.880
I'm sorry, Dr Craig, no-one else is
available and Mrs Leighton's coded.

24:03.440 --> 24:04.840
Dammit!

24:04.840 --> 24:05.880
Suction.

24:05.880 --> 24:09.880
&lt; Clear.

24:10.200 --> 24:13.800
MONITOR FLATLINES

24:13.800 --> 24:15.880
Clear.

24:15.880 --> 24:18.280
Wait five minutes,
then close if it's still dry.

24:18.280 --> 24:22.280
Trudy, give me a hand here.

24:58.520 --> 25:02.520
Apparently she'd been vomiting
and had a productive cough.

25:05.280 --> 25:06.800
Why wasn't it charted?

25:06.800 --> 25:10.800
She didn't tell anybody
except one nurse's aide.

25:11.880 --> 25:15.880
I guess she was just
so anxious to go home.

25:16.000 --> 25:18.360
She went very fast, Dr Craig.

25:18.360 --> 25:22.080
We kept the code going
for 30 minutes.

25:22.080 --> 25:23.960
I'll call the family.

25:23.960 --> 25:27.960
No, I'll do it.

26:12.360 --> 26:16.360
'Dr Romano, Dr Josef Romano
to second floor nurses' station.'

26:29.440 --> 26:31.640
I'll buy this magazine.

26:31.640 --> 26:35.640
Important to keep track for the fast
breaking trends in medicine.

26:36.160 --> 26:39.560
Keep the change, doll.

26:39.560 --> 26:40.800
Victor, Victor!

26:40.800 --> 26:42.080
Call me Dr Erlich.

26:42.080 --> 26:43.280
Thought you told me to call you...?

26:43.280 --> 26:44.680
Thought you told me to call you...?

26:44.680 --> 26:47.960
So, what's your problem, son?
Need me to save a life?

26:47.960 --> 26:49.120
No, it's parking.

26:49.120 --> 26:52.040
The security guard won't let me park
in the lot reserved for doctors.

26:52.040 --> 26:54.480
That's because you're not a doctor,
your a med student, you're nothing!

26:54.480 --> 26:55.800
That's because you're not a doctor,
your a med student, you're nothing!

26:55.800 --> 26:59.080
I mean, Dr Erlich, with Dr Caldwell
getting beaten up and everything

26:59.080 --> 27:00.600
I was afraid to park
my car anywhere else.

27:00.600 --> 27:02.240
I was afraid to park
my car anywhere else.

27:02.240 --> 27:04.040
I'm still paying for
my student loans.

27:04.040 --> 27:06.560
Well, my cousin Pee-Wee has
a Datsun dealership so...

27:06.560 --> 27:09.080
Look, Elliot, you're never going
to make it as a doctor here

27:09.080 --> 27:12.000
unless you get your mind out of the
parking lot and your butt to the ER!

27:12.000 --> 27:12.720
My car's in the middle
of the street...

27:12.720 --> 27:14.800
My car's in the middle
of the street...

27:14.800 --> 27:17.520
&lt; I'm talking life-and-death! I've
just spent six hours in OR

27:17.520 --> 27:20.400
adding 16 years to a man's life.

27:20.400 --> 27:21.440
Yes, sir.

27:21.440 --> 27:23.320
Thank you, sir.

27:23.320 --> 27:24.360
Dr Ehrlich?

27:24.360 --> 27:27.360
Wayne, I mean, Dr Fiscus
wanted me to tell you

27:27.360 --> 27:29.280
he needed you right away in the ER.

27:29.280 --> 27:31.640
Oh, something Fiscus can't
handle alone, huh?

27:31.640 --> 27:35.120
No, he said it was your turn
to change the colostomy bags.

27:35.120 --> 27:39.120
Get out of here, Elliot. Right now.
Get out, get out.

27:39.720 --> 27:41.800
Oh, no, no, this one's on me.

27:41.800 --> 27:43.480
Oh, he's cute!

27:43.480 --> 27:46.520
Thanks.

27:46.520 --> 27:49.440
Do you really have to be so rough
on the medical students?

27:49.440 --> 27:52.080
It's the only thing that'll
make them great doctors.

27:52.080 --> 27:53.480
Dr Weiss was right.

27:53.480 --> 27:56.440
He said you'd try all sorts of stupid
behaviour to try and impress me.

27:56.440 --> 27:58.520
Weiss again? Come on!

27:58.520 --> 28:00.600
No! Oh, no, Victor,
I think it's very sweet.

28:00.600 --> 28:02.000
I mean, that you care that much.

28:02.000 --> 28:03.360
Well, I do, Roberta.

28:03.360 --> 28:07.360
Well, then believe me,
I like you just as you are.

28:08.400 --> 28:11.600
I mean, you don't have to dress up
or act tough or sexy.

28:11.600 --> 28:13.280
I like the person underneath.

28:13.280 --> 28:15.360
The natural you.

28:15.360 --> 28:16.840
Natural, huh?,

28:16.840 --> 28:17.880
Completely natural?

28:17.880 --> 28:18.960
Uh-huh.

28:18.960 --> 28:22.400
Oh!

28:22.400 --> 28:23.680
What's this?

28:23.680 --> 28:24.800
A key to my apartment.

28:24.800 --> 28:25.840
Great!

28:25.840 --> 28:29.360
Er, Victor, I'd like you to stop
by tomorrow so we can talk.

28:29.360 --> 28:30.400
Fine.

28:30.400 --> 28:32.000
I'm coming in from Brookline

28:32.000 --> 28:33.960
and you can't depend
on the T with all the snow.

28:33.960 --> 28:35.760
Well, I wouldn't want you to get
locked out like you did last time.

28:35.760 --> 28:36.800
Well, I wouldn't want you to get
locked out like you did last time.

28:36.800 --> 28:38.000
OK.  (CHUCKLES)

28:38.000 --> 28:41.320
Oh...

28:41.320 --> 28:42.360
That's for you.

28:42.360 --> 28:43.560
You're kidding?

28:43.560 --> 28:45.120
So cute.

28:45.120 --> 28:49.120
Bye!

28:53.240 --> 28:55.840
So, I thought on Saturday
we'd go down to the Navy Yard

28:55.840 --> 28:59.840
and I'll show you
the USS Constitution.

29:00.000 --> 29:04.000
My dad took me there when I was
just about your age.

29:04.160 --> 29:06.840
How does that sound?

29:06.840 --> 29:10.840
And tomorrow we're going to go visit
Dr Carlisle at the hospital.

29:12.360 --> 29:14.080
It's time for your physical.

29:14.080 --> 29:16.720
She's looking forward to seeing you.

29:16.720 --> 29:20.720
Let's skip the salt and butter, OK?

29:20.880 --> 29:24.640
That's looking pretty good, son.

29:24.640 --> 29:28.640
Think we should finish it together?

29:29.280 --> 29:32.960
How's that?

29:32.960 --> 29:36.960
Here, have some pop corn.

29:41.680 --> 29:44.640
We have to talk about
something, son.

29:44.640 --> 29:47.720
Man to man.

29:47.720 --> 29:49.920
Do you remember when Mrs Catalano

29:49.920 --> 29:52.960
went to visit her
granddaughter in Buffalo?

29:52.960 --> 29:56.960
She was gone two weeks and we all
pitched in and we did just fine.

29:59.400 --> 30:02.760
Well, Mr Catalano
is going away again.

30:02.760 --> 30:06.760
This time for a lot longer.

30:06.920 --> 30:10.920
She has a sister in Italy,
just like you have Lizzie.

30:12.480 --> 30:14.880
And she wants to live with her.

30:14.880 --> 30:18.880
Do you understand?

30:28.600 --> 30:32.560
I know it's sad, son, but we're
going to be just fine. Don't worry.

30:32.560 --> 30:36.560
(WHIMPERS)

30:46.480 --> 30:49.080
EKG show bifascicular
two-to-one block

30:49.080 --> 30:51.760
with an occasional
ventricular ectopia.

30:51.760 --> 30:52.920
And your plan?

30:52.920 --> 30:54.520
Pacemaker insertion.

30:54.520 --> 30:56.040
Excellent.

30:56.040 --> 30:59.360
Dr Wade will explain the procedure
later, Mr McMullan.

30:59.360 --> 31:02.320
Don't worry, we'll take
good care of you.

31:02.320 --> 31:05.840
We'll get a urological consult
after the pacemaker is in

31:05.840 --> 31:08.560
for a probable
Small-Carrion prosthesis.

31:08.560 --> 31:09.600
Yes, sir.

31:09.600 --> 31:11.400
Anyone have any questions?

31:11.400 --> 31:15.400
All right.

31:20.640 --> 31:24.640
Dr Craig, I just wanted to say how
sorry I am...about Eve Leighton.

31:28.960 --> 31:30.720
It was a loss for all of us.

31:30.720 --> 31:32.880
It was also an extraordinary
experience.

31:32.880 --> 31:34.680
The new heart
was functioning perfectly.

31:34.680 --> 31:36.960
Your work was a success.

31:36.960 --> 31:40.960
Thank you.

31:41.760 --> 31:44.600
Well, maybe we'd better just
forget it then, I guess.

31:44.600 --> 31:46.920
Of course, if you want
to play catch?

31:46.920 --> 31:47.960
No, sir.

31:47.960 --> 31:50.360
Me either.

31:50.360 --> 31:54.120
I really don't know what you
expect from me, sir.

31:54.120 --> 31:58.120
I got a little something
for you to remind you of home.

32:02.760 --> 32:06.760
Open it, it's yours.

32:10.680 --> 32:12.160
Thank you, Dr Ridley.

32:12.160 --> 32:15.400
I've been reading all about the
Orange parade in that book there.

32:15.400 --> 32:17.520
To celebrate William's
victory at the Boyne.

32:17.520 --> 32:18.560
It's a big holiday.

32:18.560 --> 32:22.120
What, is it anything
like our Thanksgiving Day parade

32:22.120 --> 32:24.240
with floats and majorettes?

32:24.240 --> 32:27.600
Nah, it's much more
serious than that.

32:27.600 --> 32:31.120
My stepfather used to carry the drum
through the festival archways.

32:31.120 --> 32:33.080
The drum, like in the picture book?

32:33.080 --> 32:35.400
Yes, and he banged
on it with bamboo canes

32:35.400 --> 32:37.920
tied to his wrists
with leather straps.

32:37.920 --> 32:40.280
At the end of the day
he'd beat it so fiercely

32:40.280 --> 32:43.960
his arms would be all cut up.

32:43.960 --> 32:46.120
But the sound of that drum

32:46.120 --> 32:49.480
throws fear into the hearts
of all Catholics.

32:49.480 --> 32:50.960
And what about you?

32:50.960 --> 32:53.640
What would you do on that day?

32:53.640 --> 32:54.760
Pray, of course!

32:54.760 --> 32:58.760
And help to build a bonfire
to burn the Pope in effigy.

32:59.160 --> 33:00.880
And sing.

33:00.880 --> 33:02.080
Sing?

33:02.080 --> 33:03.400
What?

33:03.400 --> 33:07.400
What would you sing?

33:11.040 --> 33:14.560
# Loyal Ulstermen unite

33:14.560 --> 33:18.560
# For Ulster's cause is right

