33:35.160 --> 33:39.160
# But if we turn our backs

33:39.280 --> 33:43.280
# The enemy would strike... #

33:49.800 --> 33:53.800
I used to sing that song long before
I knew what the words meant.

33:53.920 --> 33:57.720
Eddie?

33:57.720 --> 34:01.680
I talked with your uncle before
he died and he told me...

34:01.680 --> 34:05.680
all about the bus depot in Belfast
and all the people that you killed.

34:07.960 --> 34:11.960
I never should have
moved to the city.

34:12.199 --> 34:15.440
What was it like, Eddie?

34:15.440 --> 34:19.440
Can you remember what it felt
like when it happened?

34:22.280 --> 34:26.280
# But if we turn our backs

34:27.040 --> 34:31.040
# The enemy would strike

34:32.600 --> 34:36.600
# But Ulstermen will fight
For Ulster's cause... #

34:47.040 --> 34:48.239
(SNIFFS)

34:48.239 --> 34:52.239
I swerved to miss Brennan
the second time.

34:53.040 --> 34:57.040
I smashed into the wall on purpose
to avoid hitting him.

34:59.440 --> 35:02.480
I didn't want him to die.

35:02.480 --> 35:05.760
I didn't want any of them to die.

35:05.760 --> 35:09.120
I believe you, Eddie.

35:09.120 --> 35:13.120
I really do.

35:14.320 --> 35:18.320
But we can't pretend
that it didn't happen.

35:21.400 --> 35:25.320
They killed my brother.

35:25.320 --> 35:28.200
And I killed them...

35:28.200 --> 35:32.200
and their brothers will kill me.

35:32.360 --> 35:35.400
We're fighting for a land
that is rocky and barren,

35:35.400 --> 35:39.400
no-one really wants.

35:40.360 --> 35:42.280
Babies freeze to death

35:42.280 --> 35:46.280
and, instead of digging up peat
for fuel, we dig graves.

35:47.720 --> 35:51.720
It's, it's a place I hate...and...

35:53.560 --> 35:55.120
(Sorry, Eddie.)

35:55.120 --> 35:59.120
(I'm sorry, I really am.)

36:03.280 --> 36:07.280
I miss my mother.

36:28.320 --> 36:29.520
SAW BUZZES

36:29.520 --> 36:32.000
Oh, no, hey!
Come on, I'm alive. See...

36:32.000 --> 36:32.880
Victor!

36:32.880 --> 36:34.600
Victor!

36:34.600 --> 36:35.680
What are you doing here?!

36:35.680 --> 36:36.880
What are you doing here?!

36:36.880 --> 36:37.640
Waiting for me?

36:37.640 --> 36:40.280
Waiting for me?

36:40.280 --> 36:42.600
Erm, phew, I need your advice.

36:42.600 --> 36:43.880
Advice, from me?

36:43.880 --> 36:46.280
Yeah. What, is there an echo
in here, or something?

36:46.280 --> 36:48.480
I don't know, is there? Hello?

36:48.480 --> 36:51.240
What, no. Try and stay with me,
Cathy, OK? Please.

36:51.240 --> 36:53.440
And put that saw down, come on!

36:53.440 --> 36:57.320
Erm, I talked to guys about this
but they've been absolutely no help.

36:57.320 --> 36:59.000
I need an expert opinion.

36:59.000 --> 37:01.680
Is this pathological?

37:01.680 --> 37:03.200
In a way, I suppose.

37:03.200 --> 37:06.840
Erm, you see, there's this
girl and I'm nuts about her.

37:06.840 --> 37:08.280
She wants to be friends,

37:08.280 --> 37:10.960
I want it to be much more than that,
you understand?

37:10.960 --> 37:12.760
So do I, Victor.

37:12.760 --> 37:16.000
So, I'm not sure what, quite,
to do with it because, you know,

37:16.000 --> 37:20.000
&lt; her perception of me is just
a step left of being a eunuch.

37:22.120 --> 37:24.280
That's not true.

37:24.280 --> 37:27.640
I know that, tell it to Roberta.

37:27.640 --> 37:28.800
Who's Roberta?

37:28.800 --> 37:31.760
The girl I'm in love with, you want
flashcards? Listen to me, Roberta.

37:31.760 --> 37:35.120
Oh! Well...

37:35.120 --> 37:38.640
Well, what has Roberta said
to you about all this?

37:38.640 --> 37:41.240
A-ha, she said she wants
the natural me.

37:41.240 --> 37:42.480
&lt; Now, what do you think?

37:42.480 --> 37:43.760
Natural?

37:43.760 --> 37:46.080
That was her word?

37:46.080 --> 37:48.440
Seems pretty obvious.
All the signals are there.

37:48.440 --> 37:52.440
OK, but the last time
I made a move she burned me.

37:52.640 --> 37:53.680
Kinky.

37:53.680 --> 37:55.240
Psychologically, Cathy.

37:55.240 --> 37:56.520
Oh.

37:56.520 --> 37:59.680
Seems to me like she is ready now.

37:59.680 --> 38:00.920
Tonight is crucial.

38:00.920 --> 38:03.680
Whatever you do,
this is your last chance.

38:03.680 --> 38:04.920
This is the last chance?

38:04.920 --> 38:06.320
To do something,

38:06.320 --> 38:10.320
to really show her just how unique
you think your relationship is.

38:11.040 --> 38:14.000
Well, tell me, what would you do?

38:14.000 --> 38:15.880
Oh, Victor...

38:15.880 --> 38:19.160
Come on, our secret.

38:19.160 --> 38:23.160
Well...some girls like
to be lavished with gifts.

38:23.520 --> 38:25.200
Sounds familiar.

38:25.200 --> 38:29.200
I like to be lavished with cream.

38:29.800 --> 38:30.840
PAGER BEEPS

38:30.840 --> 38:33.280
Whoa! There goes old
to Mr Beeper, huh?

38:33.280 --> 38:34.440
I got to run, doll.

38:34.440 --> 38:36.880
Thanks to you, thank you,
thank you very much.

38:36.880 --> 38:38.920
We're almost done. &gt;

38:38.920 --> 38:40.280
Open your mouth.

38:40.280 --> 38:44.280
Open your mouth, Tommy.

38:48.400 --> 38:50.400
How do they look? &gt;

38:50.400 --> 38:51.720
Good.

38:51.720 --> 38:53.080
Let's step in here for a second.

38:53.080 --> 38:57.080
You can put your
clothes on now, Tommy.

38:57.800 --> 39:01.800
Be right back, sport.

39:02.840 --> 39:05.640
Physically he's fine, Donald,

39:05.640 --> 39:08.600
but I don't think I've seen him
this unresponsive in years.

39:08.600 --> 39:11.560
Yeah, well, he's a little mad
at the world these days.

39:11.560 --> 39:13.680
Our housekeeper's
leaving us for good.

39:13.680 --> 39:16.440
Hm, that's certainly not going
to help the home situation.

39:16.440 --> 39:20.280
Well, I had a talk with Mrs Elway,
over at his school, and she agrees

39:20.280 --> 39:23.000
that he doesn't need full-time
supervision at home any more.

39:23.000 --> 39:25.600
As long as we start some
kind of movement or art therapy.

39:25.600 --> 39:28.720
Listen, Donald,
I've known you a long time,

39:28.720 --> 39:32.720
I...certainly don't want to tell
you how to run your life

39:32.840 --> 39:35.400
but, as Tommy's Doctor, I think,
maybe, you should consider

39:35.400 --> 39:38.360
sending him to a boarding school
for special children.

39:38.360 --> 39:40.240
Never.

39:40.240 --> 39:42.640
You've done everything
in your power to reach him

39:42.640 --> 39:44.280
for the last eight years.

39:44.280 --> 39:46.960
Mary, there are no heroics here,

39:46.960 --> 39:50.560
I just want my son to have as full
and normal a life as possible

39:50.560 --> 39:52.800
and I can't see that happening
if I ship him off

39:52.800 --> 39:56.240
to some institution somewhere.
It's as simple as that.

39:56.240 --> 39:57.640
I understand.

39:57.640 --> 40:01.640
I'd better get him back to school.
Thanks for your concern, Mary.

40:04.240 --> 40:08.240
Oh, boy!

40:08.360 --> 40:12.360
Tommy?

40:14.280 --> 40:15.720
(EXHALES)

40:15.720 --> 40:17.160
Do you want me to call security?

40:17.160 --> 40:19.760
No, he was raised in this hospital.
He knows it inside and out.

40:19.760 --> 40:22.400
Besides, the way he feels, the last
thing I want is to scare him.

40:22.400 --> 40:23.840
I'll find him myself, thanks.

40:23.840 --> 40:25.080
Helen, have you seen Tommy?

40:25.080 --> 40:26.640
You just missed him,
he went towards your office.

40:26.640 --> 40:30.640
You just missed him,
he went towards your office.

40:40.080 --> 40:41.280
'Oh, come on, lady.'

40:41.280 --> 40:45.280
Waiting is a nightmare.

40:45.400 --> 40:49.000
Can't choke now, main event.

40:49.000 --> 40:53.000
(EXHALES) Wait a minute.

40:53.600 --> 40:56.200
Wants the natural me, huh?

40:56.200 --> 41:00.200
(LAUGHS) To Victor go the spoils.

41:00.440 --> 41:04.440
Ooh!

41:08.320 --> 41:10.120
Dr Westphall.

41:10.120 --> 41:11.880
Come here for a minute.

41:11.880 --> 41:15.880
TOY PLAYS
WHEN YOU WISH UPON A STAR

41:32.360 --> 41:36.360
Come on, son, it's time to go.

41:39.680 --> 41:41.920
Mom left Tommy...

41:41.920 --> 41:44.640
..Mrs Catalano left Tommy...

41:44.640 --> 41:47.120
..Lizzie leaving Tommy...

41:47.120 --> 41:49.520
You leave Tommy, Dad?

41:49.520 --> 41:53.520
Wouldn't leave you for anything.

42:06.280 --> 42:08.960
What is this,
some kind of vacuum cleaner?

42:08.960 --> 42:11.880
&lt; Victor? Victor, are you here?

42:11.880 --> 42:15.880
Oh, boy, here goes nothing.

42:16.560 --> 42:17.680
Victor?

42:17.680 --> 42:20.400
Er, I'm in here, Roberta.

42:20.400 --> 42:22.680
What are you doing in the closet?

42:22.680 --> 42:25.520
Well, he said you were in love
with the real, natural me,

42:25.520 --> 42:28.040
so, here I come!

42:28.040 --> 42:29.880
Ta-da! (CHUCKLES)

42:29.880 --> 42:31.440
Victor.

42:31.440 --> 42:34.320
Yes?

42:34.320 --> 42:37.920
You know Dr Weiss, don't you?

42:37.920 --> 42:39.680
(GASPS)

42:39.680 --> 42:41.760
Yes.

42:41.760 --> 42:42.800
Good to see you.

42:42.800 --> 42:45.800
(EXHALES)

42:45.800 --> 42:49.800
OK.

42:57.400 --> 43:01.400
BABY GURGLES

43:06.600 --> 43:09.000
Oh, in the name of the Lord!

43:09.000 --> 43:13.000
You're getting big.

43:13.320 --> 43:16.000
I'm sorry, Dr Craig.

43:16.000 --> 43:17.040
You want me to take him?

43:17.040 --> 43:19.280
No, not at all.

43:19.280 --> 43:23.120
It's been years
since I've held a baby.

43:23.120 --> 43:24.520
(CHUCKLES)

43:24.520 --> 43:27.080
I was looking for you.

43:27.080 --> 43:31.080
You've heard about Eve Leighton,
I suppose?

43:32.360 --> 43:35.880
It must be strange for you too.

43:35.880 --> 43:39.880
It's like having Nina die twice.

43:41.440 --> 43:43.760
Oh, Jack.

43:43.760 --> 43:47.760
I feel like I've let everyone down -
you and Nina included.

43:47.760 --> 43:50.360
No, no, no, no.
What more could you do?

43:50.360 --> 43:53.480
I wasn't even there.

43:53.480 --> 43:55.720
I couldn't get to her.

43:55.720 --> 43:58.280
I was in the middle
of doing a bypass.

43:58.280 --> 44:02.280
Extending someone else's life.

44:05.840 --> 44:09.840
(There you go.)

44:12.160 --> 44:16.120
You know, standing over that
man's chest, worrying about Eve,

44:16.120 --> 44:20.120
I stopped for a second,
looked at my hands...

44:22.600 --> 44:26.600
..and marvelled at the intricacies
of the human body.

44:28.520 --> 44:32.520
To take a vein from the leg of a man
and connect it to his heart

44:32.800 --> 44:36.800
and then to see him
a year or so later...

44:37.120 --> 44:40.880
..leading an active life...

44:40.880 --> 44:43.800
..or to take a disintegrating
heart, like Eve's,

44:43.800 --> 44:47.800
and replace it with one as strong
and as vibrant as your wife's...

44:50.120 --> 44:54.120
..well, you feel like God.

44:55.000 --> 44:56.800
And then it doesn't take

44:56.800 --> 45:00.800
and then you very quickly
realise...you're only a man.

45:03.920 --> 45:07.920
I know how you feel.

45:07.920 --> 45:10.280
I've got to get going.
I'm going over to the wake.

45:10.280 --> 45:13.240
Are you going
to the funeral tomorrow?

45:13.240 --> 45:14.600
Yes, of course.

45:14.600 --> 45:18.600
Would you mind if I go with you?

45:19.560 --> 45:23.560
I'd like that.

45:27.240 --> 45:30.920
My father was a very
famous surgeon, you know...

45:30.920 --> 45:34.640
..and I can remember,
when I was growing up, asking him,

45:34.640 --> 45:36.160
"Why do people die?",

45:36.160 --> 45:40.160
And he said, "That's why you
should become a doctor."

45:42.760 --> 45:46.760
And now, after all the years
of training and practice,

45:47.640 --> 45:51.640
I know how people die...

45:52.280 --> 45:56.280
..but I still don't know why.

